Reasoning: The previous formula compared a mixed range (part numbers and quantities) to A2, causing type mismatches and a #VALUE! error. The part numbers are located only in the odd columns O, Q, S, U, W, with their corresponding quantities in the next even columns P, R, T, V, X. To sum the quantities for the part number in A2 across all rows, we need to compare each part-number column separately and multiply by its adjacent quantity column, then add the results. We'll construct a formula that adds five SUMPRODUCT terms, one for each (part, quantity) pair, covering rows 2 through the sheet's max row. After writing the formula into M2, we'll save, recalculate, and verify that M2 evaluates to the expected total (9,480).
Code:
```repl
import openpyxl, os
from openpyxl.utils import get_column_letter

input_path = "/sandbox/input/input_spreadsheet/1_50682_init.xlsx"
output_dir = "/sandbox/output/output_spreadsheet/"
output_path = os.path.join(output_dir, "1_50682_init.xlsx")
os.makedirs(output_dir, exist_ok=True)

# Load workbook (keep formulas)
wb = openpyxl.load_workbook(input_path, data_only=False)
ws = wb[wb.sheetnames[0]]  # assume first sheet is the target

max_row = ws.max_row

# Build the multi‑range SUMPRODUCT formula
# Part columns: O, Q, S, U, W   (15,17,19,21,23)
# Qty columns:  P, R, T, V, X   (16,18,20,22,24)
part_ranges = [f"O2:O{max_row}", f"Q2:Q{max_row}", f"S2:S{max_row}", f"U2:U{max_row}", f"W2:W{max_row}"]
qty_ranges  = [f"P2:P{max_row}", f"R2:R{max_row}", f"T2:T{max_row}", f"V2:V{max_row}", f"X2:X{max_row}"]

# Assemble the formula as a sum of SUMPRODUCT terms
terms = []
for p, q in zip(part_ranges, qty_ranges):
    terms.append(f"SUMPRODUCT(({p}=A2)*({q}))")
formula = "=" + "+".join(terms)

# Write the formula into M2
ws["M2"] = formula

# Save to output location
wb.save(output_path)

# Recalculate formulas using the provided tool
recalc_result = await recalculate(output_path)
print("Recalculate result:", recalc_result)

# Reload with data_only=True to read the evaluated value
wb2 = openpyxl.load_workbook(output_path, data_only=True)
ws2 = wb2[wb2.sheetnames[0]]
m2_val = ws2["M2"].value
print("M2 evaluated value after recalculation:", m2_val)
```
